He holds that the lex Julia connects immediately with the lex Calpurnia of Rc. 149: that intermediate laws dealt with repetundae not by itself but only in connection with other official offences Ξ that down to the time of the lex Aurelia of 13.c. 70 there was a recognised distinction, acknowledged by Sulla, between official offences and ordinary offences, and a distinct procedure for each. Thus the persons liable under the lex Cornelia de repetundis must have been (a) all senatorial Officers, (b) all senators, (c) certain officials whose office was the first step to promotion. But the lex Julia of Caesar included not only senators and senatorial officers, but also other persons who exercised a share of the state-control. As to Rab.
